title: For Sale:  Forged M14 / M1a Polytec, USGI Bolt & op rod, 4th Gen rail, polymer riser
postcontent:
The Polytec M1a's had a top of the line forged receiver that's stronger, more durable, and ironically holds more accurately to USGI spec than the commercial Springfield M1a productions since the late 80's.  The rest of the Polytec rifles are sub-optimal. [grin]  I've replaced the bolt and op rod w/ USGI parts, properly headspaced.  

I put one of the newer over-the-reciever picatinny rails on her, and a polymer adjustable cheek riser on the stock.  

She still has the original chinese (low quality, in my opinion) wooden stock, 22.5" (I think) barrel w/ USGI style flash suppressor & bayonet mount, and trigger.  The trigger actually isn't that bad -- I've had current production Springfield triggers that were worse.  

She's been in our family for a long time, and is a fine, reliable, 1.5 moa rifle. 

I'm only considering selling her to fund vehicle repairs, and will keep her if I can get everything squared away.

I've sold the Elcan that was on her, but do have a few other optics I could add to her - Aimpoint CompM3, etc.

title: For Sale:  1850s? era Blunderbuss
postcontent:
Blunderbuss.
I have a 1850s area percussion Blunderbuss for sale. I’m not sure of its origin because I can’t find any proof marks anywhere. I believe it is under the barrel. I am afraid to remove the barrel, as I do not have the proper tools. There is some etching on all the screws and trigger plate, butt plate and hammer. The barrel is elliptical shaped and made of steel. Overall the condition is excellent. I tried to research this gun, via the Internet, and found one real similar, almost exact. That one was made in Belgium.

The guy I bought this from had it in his family for several years, he told me he and his grandpa shot it last back in the early 70s. This gun has been very well taken care of, the stock has some scuffs/small dents but has no cracks or splits. Very good condition for its age. I took this gun to a gun shop and they confirmed that this is an original not a replica, they too were afraid to take the barrel off.

The receiver has had the bolt raceway trued, bolt lugs lapped and faced, threads trued, and bolt body replaced with a custom spiral fluted bolt w/a Badger Ordnance Tac knob added. The Lawton Heavy profile barrel is 27" to the threads, chambered, and crowned then fitted to the receiver and stock in front of a Badger Ordnance stainless Heavy Recoil Lug... a Vias muzzle brake was added to reduce recoil. McIntyre precision upgraded the trigger with their tier 1 enhancement package.

It sits in the original H/S precision aluminum pillar bedded Kevlar stock, but the Badger Ordnance M5 DBM system has been added (detachable box mag) and includes 2xBadger Ordnance (AICS) 5rd magazines. On top is a Ken Farrell G-Force scope base to guarantee a rock solid mount.
Has seen only light range use, 100rds fired.  

Asking $1650 in Tacoma… can ship if needed/drive to meet

title: For Sale:   COLT  "Transition" - BANGER`
postcontent: COLT "Transition" manufactured in 1924. This pistol by serial number was shipped on July 25th 1924, in a lot of 2850, Commanding Officer to the Springfield Armory. This is the most beautiful Transition I have ever owned retaining 100% of the GORGEOUS Pre-War oven blued finish. Most 1924's are worn or handled to the point where the finish begins to darken or is worn away. Not this perfect specimen of Pre-War Colt craftsmanship! This is what Transitions must have looked like when they were factory new. The 1937 "replacement" slide matches the lower perfectly and is stamped with the frame serial number under the FP stop. It is my opinion that the original upper was lost or damaged and was replaced at the factory with this slide during or after 1937. Again, as you can see in the pictures, the slide matches the receiver perfectly. Finishing this off this fine pistol are the original walnut 28LPI checkered grips. Please use the pictures as proof of actual condition.
